y of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so called, such as Frome (Somerset), Frome Saint Quintin, Frome Vauchurch, Frome Whitfield in Stinsford, the lost <i>Frome Billet</i> in West Stafford (all Dorset), Bishops Frome, Canon Frome, Castle Frome, and Prior's Frome and Larport (formerly <i>Frome</i>) both in Mordiford (all Herefordshire). Or a topographic name from the rivers on which these places are located, or simply a name for someone living beside a river of this name, which is probably cognate with Welsh <i>ffraw</i> ‘fair, fine, brisk’. Compare   Frampton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Frampton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so called, of which there are several in Gloucestershire, one in Dorset and one in Lincolnshire. Most take the name from the Frome river in south Gloucestershire (which is probably from a British word meaning ‘fair, brisk’) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. One near Tewkesbury was originally named in Old English as <i>Frēolingtūn</i> ‘settlement associated with <i>Frēola</i>’, a short form of any of various compound personal names with the first element <i>frēo</i> ‘free’. Frampton in Lincolnshire probably gets its name from an Old English byname <i>Frameca</i> (a derivative of <i>fram</i> ‘valiant’) + <i>tūn</i>."]},{"name":"Froom","meanings":["English: variant of   Frome  .","German: from a short form of a personal name composed with Middle High German <i>vrom</i>, <i>vrum</i> ‘valiant, steadfast’ (see   Frommelt  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Frome was born about 1330, in Woodlands, Dorset, England, his father, John Frome, was 33 and his mother, Amey Spigornell, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth de Braose."},"et":{"about 1330–":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1363–1404":"1363–1404","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"umbes 1330","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Woodlands, Dorset, England":"Woodlands, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1330–":"noin 1330–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1346–Female":"1346–Kuollut","1363–1404":"1363–1404","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","1346":"1346","1300":"130